1.15 We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to the following:
a. Assign an adequate number of members that will compose the Inventory Committee and temporarily relieve them of their regular duties to devote their full time to the conduct of the physical inventory taking until completion of the activity;
b. Submit to the Office of the Auditor duly approved Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) containing the specific assignments/duties of the Committee Members, the cut-off date, and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory-taking activities from start-up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory. Section 5.11 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 required that a copy of the duly approved PIP shall be submitted to COA at least ten (10) days before the scheduled date of inventory;
c. The Inventory Committee strictly comply with the procedural guidelines stated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fast track the completion of the conduct of the physical count of PPE by determining the properties found at the station, missing or non-existing PPEs, and the condition of the property items whether serviceable or not, and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly approved Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment of all properties owned by the City;
d. The CAO and CGSO undertake and complete the procedures under Items 6.3.1 and 6.3.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
e. Property and Accounting Units shall undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor and the City Accountant:
Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances totaling ₱9,119,721.65 pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively;
Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers and employees with overdue accounts;
Continue the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 especially to officials and employees in active service;
Request for the write off of long outstanding cash advances aged 10 years and over especially for those who have been deceased following the procedures under COA Circular No. 2016-005, dated December 19, 2016; and
Ensure that no additional cash advances shall be granted to officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the City Accountant:
Evaluate payables included in the schedule of Accounts Payable to determine if they are valid obligations of the City to suppliers/contractors, City officials/employees and other payees;
Prepare adjusting entry for payables which did not pass the recognition criteria of a liability as defined under MNGAS, Volume I and the related regulation provided under Section 157 of GAAM, Volume I by debiting Accounts Payable and crediting Due to Officers and Employees/Due to Other LGUs / Prior Period Adjustments;
Recognize liability and record under accounts payable only when goods and services are accepted or rendered and supplier/creditor bills are received pursuant to Section 4, Chapter 2 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, and when supported by sufficient evidence and there is proper authority for its incurrence in conformity with Section 157 of GAAM, Volume 1; and
Propose to the Sangguniang Panlungsod upon approval of the City Mayor, the reversion to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund the Accounts Payable which are outstanding in the books for more than two years and against which no actual claim, administrative or judicial, has been filed or which is not covered by perfected contracts on record in consonance with Section 98 of PD No. 1445.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the City Mayor and the City Accountant:

a)	Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances totaling ₱9,326,073.70 pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively;

b)	Prioritize issuance of demand letter to all accountable officers and employees with overdue accounts;

c)	Continue the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 especially to officials and employees in active service;

d)	Request for the write off of long outstanding cash advances aged 10 years and over especially to those who have been deceased following the procedures under COA Circular No. 2016-005, dated December 19, 2016; and

e)	Ensure that no additional cash advances shall be granted to those officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

We recommended that:  

a)	The City Treasurer prepare and submit List of Real Property Tax Delinquencies as of December 31, 2020 to determine the actual RPT/SET Receivable as basis in adjusting the abnormal balances;

b)	The City Assessor prepare and submit an updated Assessment Roll at the beginning of the year pursuant to City Revenue Code and Section 212 of RA No. 7160;   

c)	Require the City Accountant to establish in the books of GF and SEF:

•	the actual RPT/SET Receivables for prior years based on the List of Real Property Tax Delinquencies and to adjust the abnormal balances;

•	the RPT/SET Receivables for the current year based on updated Assessment Roll pursuant to the requirements of Section 19.b, Chapter 3 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, for fair presentation of the receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the City Accountant:

Prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to take up all valid book reconciling items at once after the bank reconciliation process is finished pursuant to Section 3.3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996 to ascertain the correctness of balances of Cash-in-Bank-LCCA;

Make written representation to the bank regarding bank reconciling items not acted.  Otherwise, appropriate adjustment must be prepared for bank discrepancies that the bank will certainly not consider; 

Hereafter, promptly inform the bank of any error or discrepancy noted while the documents are still available to ensure that correction is carried out in the subsequent bank statement; and

The discrepancies must be thoroughly investigated to determine the person(s) responsible for the error, either the City or the Bank so it could be promptly corrected.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Direct the City Engineer to call the attention of the concerned contractors with project deficiencies to make good the defects noted by immediately conducting repair/completion of the evacuation centers and school feeding centers so the projects could serve their purposes;

Instruct all Project Engineers or Project In-charge to track the accomplishments of the contractors and communicate to the City Engineer any deficiencies noted in project implementation so that the same will be addressed promptly;

Instruct the CPDO to monitor and evaluate the implementation of all development projects of the City pursuant to the Sec. 476 (4) of the LGC to ensure that these projects are implemented properly and in accordance with the plans and specifications per contract signed by both parties;

Assign personnel or other members of the City School Board to check all projects funded by SEF to make certain that they are implemented properly and in accordance with the plans and specifications provided in the contract; and 

Advise the Inspectorate Committee to conduct actual inspection on the project completion and not rely on the Accomplishment Report of the contractor and reprimand them for failure to perform their task satisfactorily.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
      Mandatory Segregation of Solid Wastes

Enforce strict implementation of the mandatory segregation of solid wastes at the barangay level pursuant to the provisions of Sections 21 and 22 of RA No. 9003 so that only non-biodegradable wastes are dumped at the SLF; 

 Establishment of LGU Materials Recovery Facility (MRF)

Establish Material Recovery Facility (MRF) at the Public Market, SLF and in all barangays in accordance with Section 32 of RA No. 9003; 
       Establishment of Mandatory Solid Waste Diversion

Direct the Head of CENRO to:

Facilitate procurement of one-unit Transformer (10 KVA) so that the Shredders and Water Treatment Facilities would be utilized for the intended purposes at the SLF site; 
Strictly comply with the diversion of at least 25% of all solid wastes from waste disposal facilities through re-use, recycling and composting activities in consonance with Section 20 of RA             No. 9003; 

Operating Criteria for Sanitary Landfill

Prioritize the acquisition of an additional brand-new bulldozer or compactor to complement the one functional bulldozer at the SLF site and/ or include in the budget additional allocation for sanitary land fill site adjacent or near the existing SLF site, which will serve as an alternate cell for solid wastes and for possible condemnation of the currently almost full disposal facility; and

Ensure that one-month stockpile of intermediate soil cover materials for the landfill must always be available on the site.

We recommended that the City Mayor and the City Treasurer implement the following measures:
Immediately require Mr. Balquin to return to the City the missing funds totaling ₱918,219.42
Direct the withholding of Mr. Balquin’s salaries and other monies due him, cancel his fidelity bond and file appropriate charges for failure to perform his duties honestly and diligently;
Designate a new Cashier to be closely supervised by the City Treasurer to ensure that government funds in his/her custody are fully accounted for in accordance with laws, rules and regulations;
Require explanation from the City Treasurer for her failure to closely supervise the Cashier which give him the opportunity to misappropriate the funds in his  custody and why she should not be charged administratively  for dereliction of duty;
Ensure that the newly designated Cashier deposit collections intact daily to the government depository bank and enforce recording of collections daily in the cash book pursuant to Sections 32 and 26 of MNGAS for LGUs Volume I and Volume II, respectively;
Strictly grant cash advance to AO without outstanding cash advances in consonance with Paragraph 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
Require all DOs to stop the practice of transferring their cash advances to other DO’s and to record promptly their paid payrolls in the cash disbursement cash books, pursuant to the provisions of Section 75 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
Constitute a PMT to undertake the monitoring of all infrastructure projects implemented by the City;

Direct the City Engineer/Project Engineer to submit written explanation why payment was recommended even though some deficiencies were not corrected by the contractor;

Require the contractor to rectify the deficiencies noted or undertake repair works at once pursuant to Section 62 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulation of RA 9184;  

Direct the CPDC and City Engineer to expedite execution of infrastructure projects based on contract time; and

Ensure that government funds for infrastructure projects are managed and utilized in accordance with the purpose for which they are appropriated and safeguarded against wastage so the projects could benefit the City’s constituents.

