Require explanation from the City Treasurer for her failure to closely supervise the Cashier which give him the opportunity to misappropriate the funds in his  custody and why she should not be charged administratively  for dereliction of duty;
Ensure that the newly designated Cashier deposit collections intact daily to the government depository bank and enforce recording of collections daily in the cash book pursuant to Sections 32 and 26 of MNGAS for LGUs Volume I and Volume II, respectively;
Strictly grant cash advance to AO without outstanding cash advances in consonance with Paragraph 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
Require all DOs to stop the practice of transferring their cash advances to other DO’s and to record promptly their paid payrolls in the cash disbursement cash books, pursuant to the provisions of Section 75 of           P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended and Management agreed:
That the City Mayor and the City Accountant -
Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances especially those granted prior to December 31, 2011 totaling ₱17,632,045.28 pursuant to Section 6.0 of COA Circular No. 2012-004 dated  November 28, 2012;
Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers who are still in active service;
Impose the withholding of salary and institute other sanctions as provided for under Sections 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 to those employees who fail to liquidate their cash advances after the demand letters are issued to them;
Immediately send a follow up letter to COA-ICFAU to ascertain the status of previously submitted liquidation documents for charges against confidential fund for CYs 1999-2012 and request issuance of credit advice and credit notice;
Ensure that no additional cash advances be granted to those officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and Item 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 22, 1997;
Require retiring accountable official or employee to undertake an authorization (in affidavit form) to deduct financial obligations including unliquidated cash advance from the terminal leave benefits pursuant to 5.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
Require officials and employees who intend to transfer to another office to liquidate their cash advance before Clearance from Property and Money Accountabilities is released to ensure settlement of accounts; and
Assign personnel in the Accounting Office to closely monitor the movement of the long outstanding cash advances and to prepare quarterly report copy furnished the Auditor, for possible write-off of dormant or long outstanding unliquidated cash advances pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We reiterated the following recommendation:
That the City Mayor -
Enforce  strict implementation of the mandatory segregation of solid wastes at the barangay level pursuant to the provisions of Sections 21 and 22 of RA No. 9003;
Establish Material Recovery Facility (MRF) at the Public Market and in all barangays in accordance with Section 32 of RA No. 9003; and
Direct the Head of CENRO:
To submit a report on the condition of the three unserviceable heavy equipment at the SLF considering that the same were acquired only on May 15, 2013;
To consider disposal as an option if the heavy equipment are found to be beyond repair;
To strictly comply with the diversion of at least 25% of all solid wastes from waste disposal facilities through re-use, recycling and composting activities in consonance with Section 20 of RA No. 9003; and
To facilitate compliance with the conditions of ECC –
undertake quarterly monitoring of groundwater monitoring wells to ensure early detection of the occurrence of water contamination in compliance with the conditions of ECC;
that one month stockpile of intermediate soil cover materials for the landfill must always be available on the site; and
that immediate compaction of loosed and newly exposed areas shall be undertaken.  Install sediment trasp/setting pond whenever necessary and install perimeter fence.

The CSWDO widen the scope of programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to be included in the GPB which should give more focus on the welfare of women and children instead of giving preference to programs and activities for social services and livelihood;

It should make sure that in the succeeding year, electrification, especially in crime-prone areas to prevent incidence of crimes  are included in the mainstreaming of GAD programs and projects;

Also, incorporate in the GAD Plan seminars and symposia wherein the weaker members of society such as women and children be trained on how to defend themselves in case of attacks from bad elements of society;

The GAD Committee and CSWD include in the GAD  mainstreaming, a water supply project for the housing units at Barangay Tiglawigan to solve the problem so that  inhabitants thereat will no longer fetch water from a distant place; and

Lastly, it should also include in the GAD Plan programs for the welfare of out-of-school street children, particularly, the Children in Conflict With Law (CCWL) or it may also be mainstreamed and incorporated in the programs of the Local Council for the Protection of Children, so they will not become social menace but will have a great part in nation building.

The City Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the required physical inventory of government properties since this deficiency has long been reported in the annual report and no sincere efforts on the part of management to comply with the mandated requirement;

The GSO to maintain Property Cards for all properties purchased by the City which should be regularly updated.  Additionally, the PAR must be renewed every three years or every time there is a change in custodianship/user of the property; and

The Accounting Office to maintain PPE ledger cards for each asset category and Real Property cards for land owned by the City.  All concerned must ensure that the documents are regularly updated to facilitate the conduct of a complete physical inventory of LGU properties to support the City’s billion-peso property items as reflected in the year-end Statement of Financial Position.

The City Mayor and the City Accountant ensure the immediate liquidation of long outstanding and non-moving advances especially those officials and employees who are still in active service; 

The City Accountant strictly require officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed periods pursuant to 5.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002; and

The City Accountant make certain that no additional cash advances shall be granted to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted to him has been settled or a proper accounting thereof has been made pursuant to                Section 89 of               PD No. 1445.

